Chapters

… but also through their digital transformation

Digital transformation and e-commerce are of increasing importance for luxury brands.

Digitalisation of the luxury industry is nothing new for LVMH. But since the pandemic, all LVMH Maisons have taken digitalisation to the next level, reinventing experiences for our clients. 

 

How can our digital age enrich a luxurious experience?


LVMH embraced the digital world quite early on – with the eLuxury platform in the early 2000’s, or Louis Vuitton’s first e-commerce website in 2005. But truth be told, there have been questions and moments of trepidation along the way. There still are, occasionally – because of the deeply rooted perception that the “true” luxury experience takes place in a store.

For the client, a trip to a store, as pleasant as it may be, is sometimes no match to the gratification of conveniently shopping online from the comfort of their home, followed by a delivery to the place and at the time of their choice. The ability to shop anywhere, anytime is their luxury. That’s how the digital age has broadened and enriched, not restricted or tarnished, the concept of a luxurious experience.

 

Physical and visual interactions share the notion of excellence 


For a client to be able to stay in touch with their favorite advisor and continue to shop even while the store is closed (say, during a pandemic!) is also a newer facet of luxury. Digital technologies have allowed us to dematerialise the experience that was once tied and constrained by a physical space, a cash register, physical products, and an in-person exchange. Most critically, technology has allowed us to do so without degrading the quality of the interaction.

 

The point hasn’t been to literally replicate a physical store visit in the digital world. Much more impactful than that, digital technologies have allowed clients to discover a broader product range than they would in most stores and peruse them more quickly and efficiently thanks to “searchandising” techniques such as filters or preferences, for example. There is also the additional benefit of easily zooming in and out to discover more about each product in a greater level of detail, instantaneously (e.g. what materials or ingredients a given item is made of, what other colorways or sizes it is available in, etc.). The fact that there aren’t any physical constraints to how many products can be featured in a digital store, or how much additional engaging information and services you can provide around the product discovery experience, is where the concept of a digital flagship comes in.

 

Ideally, that flagship experience will also be enriched with readily available content about the brand: its craftsmanship, the stories that made each brand’s history – in other words, compelling storytelling, once the remit of sales advisors only, now supported by close-ups, videos and interactive tools. The digital experience is initiated by the client, at their own pace and depending on where they fit, at that moment in time, in the “funnel”- i.e. looking for inspiration, guidance, consideration, reassurance, etc.

 

Every client is unique and deserves a unique and personalised experience


The ability to leverage the incredible power of data to personalise the experience provided to each client creates a whole new dimension to the definition of luxury. Imagine a unique store for every client, where each client is presented with a selection of products and services just right for them, with the right amount of the unexpected as well. Creativity and the element of surprise should not be neglected and should, on the contrary, be included in how our algorithms are built in order to continuously surprise and delight our clients, appeal to their senses and provoke an emotional reaction.

 

It is also critical to understand how the notion of service, which lies at the core of the luxury business, has been facilitated, if not amplified, thanks to digital technologies in recent years. Clients can now easily reach out to an advisor via a chat feature or video call from our brands’ websites. More and more, they have the option to set up an appointment online and decide if that appointment should take place in a store or virtually. They can get personalised skincare or styling advice. And all those services can be offered in a more flexible fashion than ever before – on demand and at scale, thanks, once again, to the marriage of artificial intelligence and human interaction.

Artificial intelligence and machine learning also give client advisors “super powers” that help them better anticipate their clients’ needs and tastes – sometimes even before their clients realise it. How? For example, by helping them deepen their knowledge of their clients and enhance (not replace) their own expert intuition via AI-driven “hints” as to which clients are most likely to be interested in this or that type of product at a certain point in time. All of that is typically available at their fingertips in a small device called a mobile phone. What’s incredibly powerful for the client advisor is also incredibly beneficial to the client, who is no longer served “one size fits all” messages… Win-win!

 

Digitalisation also means exploring new horizons


The beauty of the digitalisation topic is that it is a seemingly never-ending process incorporating newer, faster, richer features that contribute to the beauty of the luxury experience. Among the many trends informing our brands’ strategies in recent years is the increasingly omnichannel behaviors of our clients. They care about our brands, our products, and our services. The “channels” in which those can be accessed are a marketing construct and are irrelevant to clients. They should be to us as well.

 

For whoever had any doubt left about it, 2020 made the whole omnichannel concept very, very real when entire populations went into lockdown and stores closed. Our luxury clients showed us how important it was for them to be able to continue to dream, find inspiration, and yes, shop in a way that was free of physical constraints and channel siloes. By the same token, it became clear to us that we had to “show up”, be where our clients expected us to be, and sometimes go where luxury brands had never gone before. Isn’t breaking new frontiers, exploring new horizons, and reinventing oneself also part of the very essence of luxury?
